Table functions cannot accept table arguments containing collated columns, as this limitation prevents mixing collation specifications across function boundaries. This query demonstrates the restriction by attempting to call a user-defined table function with a SELECT statement that produces a collated column, which will fail with an error message indicating that collation specifications are not allowed on table function arguments.

```googlesql
CREATE TABLE FUNCTION my_dataset.my_tvf(x TABLE<col_str STRING>) AS (
  SELECT col_str FROM x
);

SELECT * FROM my_dataset.my_tvf(
  (SELECT COLLATE('abc', 'und:ci') AS col_str)
);
```

The `HIDDEN` attribute prevents a column from appearing in `SELECT *` expansions. A generated column with `HIDDEN` on its source columns can combine those columns without exposing the individual inputs.

```googlesql
CREATE TABLE Authors (
  first_name STRING HIDDEN,
  last_name STRING HIDDEN,
  full_name STRING GENERATED ALWAYS AS (CONCAT(first_name, ' ', last_name));
);
```

The `CREATE PROCEDURE` statement defines a reusable block of SQL statements. Parameter modes (`IN`, `OUT`, `INOUT`) specify whether each parameter is used for input, output, or both. The procedure body contains SQL statements wrapped in a `BEGIN...END` block.

```sql
CREATE PROCEDURE my_procedure(IN x INT64, OUT y STRING)
BEGIN
  IF x > 0 THEN
    SET y = 'positive';
  ELSE
    SET y = 'non-positive';
  END IF;
END;
```

Nested messages are set using nested braces, and array fields use square brackets containing multiple struct constructors for each element.

```googlesql
SELECT
  NEW googlesql.examples.music.Album {
    album_name: 'New Moon'
    singer {
      nationality: 'Canadian'
      residence: [ { city: 'Victoria' }, { city: 'Toronto' } ]
    }
    song: ['Sandstorm', 'Wait']
  }
```

The ASSERT statement evaluates the condition COUNT(*) > 5 and succeeds silently if true. If the condition is false or NULL, it generates an error with the custom description provided in the AS clause. This example demonstrates a successful assertion—the dataset has 6 rows, so the condition is satisfied and no error is produced.

```googlesql
ASSERT (
  (SELECT COUNT(*) > 5 FROM UNNEST([1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]))
) AS 'Table must contain more than 5 rows.';
```

The ASSERT statement evaluates the condition COUNT(*) > 10, which is FALSE because the dataset only contains 6 rows. When an assertion fails, GoogleSQL generates an error and displays the custom error message provided in the AS clause. This example demonstrates the failure case where the row count does not meet the required threshold.

```googlesql
ASSERT (
  (SELECT COUNT(*) > 10 FROM UNNEST([1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]))
) AS 'Table must contain more than 10 rows.';
```

The CAST function with the FORMAT clause converts a time to a string. The AM and PM format elements output the meridian indicator based on whether the time is before or after noon.

```googlesql
SELECT CAST(TIME '21:30:00' AS STRING FORMAT 'AM') AS date_time_to_string;
SELECT CAST(TIME '21:30:00' AS STRING FORMAT 'PM') AS date_time_to_string;
```

The CAST function with the FORMAT clause converts a time to a string. The AM and PM format elements output the appropriate meridian indicator for the given time.

```googlesql
SELECT CAST(TIME '01:30:00' AS STRING FORMAT 'AM') AS date_time_to_string;
SELECT CAST(TIME '01:30:00' AS STRING FORMAT 'PM') AS date_time_to_string;
```

`ST_GEOGFROM` converts a GeoJSON-formatted string to a GEOGRAPHY value, supporting standard GeoJSON geometry definitions.

```googlesql
SELECT ST_GEOGFROM(
  '{ "type": "Polygon", "coordinates": [ [ [2, 0], [2, 2], [1, 2], [0, 2], [0, 0], [2, 0] ] ] }'
) AS GEOJSON_format;
```

In a `CALL` subquery, you can use column aliases in the subquery's `RETURN` statement to rename columns and prevent conflicts with outer-scope columns. This example aliases the account ID to avoid conflicts with the person ID.

```googlesql
GRAPH FinGraph
MATCH (p:Person {Id: 1})
CALL (p) {
  MATCH (p)-[:Owns]->(a:Account)
  RETURN a.Id AS account_Id
}
RETURN p.Id AS person_Id, account_Id;
```

Nested `CALL` statements with explicit variable scope lists allow you to pass multiple variables from outer scopes into inner subqueries. This example counts internal transfers (between accounts of the same person) using nested scoping.

```googlesql
GRAPH FinGraph
MATCH (p:Person {Id:2})
CALL (p) {
  MATCH (p)-[:Owns]->(a:Account)
  OPTIONAL CALL (p, a) {
    MATCH (a)-[t:Transfers]->(other:Account), (p)-[:Owns]->(other)
    RETURN count(t) AS num_internal_transfers
  }
  RETURN a.Id AS account_Id, COALESCE(num_internal_transfers, 0) AS internal_transfers
}
RETURN p.name, account_Id, internal_transfers
ORDER BY account_Id;
```

This query uses an `EXISTS` subquery to verify whether at least one matching row exists. The subquery searches for a person named "Lee" with an ownership relationship to an account, and returns `TRUE` if found.

```googlesql
GRAPH FinGraph
RETURN EXISTS {
  MATCH (p:Person {Name: "Lee"})-[o:Owns]->(a:Account)
  RETURN p.Name
  LIMIT 1
} AS results;
```

This query uses an `EXISTS` subquery with only a `MATCH` statement, omitting the `RETURN` clause. The subquery still evaluates to `TRUE` if the pattern matches at least one row, even without specifying what to return.

```googlesql
GRAPH FinGraph
RETURN EXISTS {
  MATCH (p:Person {Name: "Lee"})-[o:Owns]->(a:Account)
} AS results;
```

This query uses an `EXISTS` subquery with only a graph pattern expression, bypassing the `MATCH` statement entirely. The subquery returns `TRUE` if the pattern finds at least one matching path in the graph.

```googlesql
GRAPH FinGraph
RETURN EXISTS {
  (p:Person {Name: "Lee"})-[o:Owns]->(a:Account)
} AS results;
```

This query uses an `IN` subquery to test whether a specific value exists in the subquery results. It returns `TRUE` if the name "Dana" is found among all person names returned by the match expression.

```googlesql
GRAPH FinGraph
RETURN 'Dana' IN {
  MATCH (p:Person)-[o:Owns]->(a:Account)
  RETURN p.name
} AS results;
```

This query uses a `VALUE` subquery to extract a single scalar value from the subquery result. The subquery matches a person with `country: "Australia"` and returns their name; the `LIMIT 1` ensures exactly one row is produced, which becomes the scalar result.

```googlesql
GRAPH FinGraph
RETURN VALUE {
  MATCH (p:Person {country: "Australia"})
  RETURN p.name
  LIMIT 1
} AS results;
```

The `JSON_EXTRACT_ARRAY` function extracts a JSON array and converts it to a SQL `ARRAY<JSON>` or `ARRAY<JSON-formatted STRING>` value.

```googlesql
SELECT JSON_EXTRACT_ARRAY(
  JSON '{"fruits":["apples","oranges","grapes"]}','$.fruits'
  ) AS json_array;
```

Combine `JSON_EXTRACT_ARRAY` with `CAST` and `UNNEST` to extract and convert JSON array elements to a specific SQL type.

```googlesql
SELECT ARRAY(
  SELECT CAST(integer_element AS INT64)
  FROM UNNEST(
    JSON_EXTRACT_ARRAY('[1,2,3]','$')
  ) AS integer_element
) AS integer_array;
```

The `JSON_EXTRACT_ARRAY` function accepts both dot-notation and bracket-notation to access the same array path.

```googlesql
SELECT JSON_EXTRACT_ARRAY('{"fruits": ["apples", "oranges", "grapes"]}', '$[fruits]') AS string_array;

SELECT JSON_EXTRACT_ARRAY('{"fruits": ["apples", "oranges", "grapes"]}', '$.fruits') AS string_array;
```

The `JSON_EXTRACT_STRING_ARRAY` function extracts a JSON array of strings and returns them as a SQL `ARRAY<STRING>` with quotes removed.

```googlesql
SELECT JSON_EXTRACT_STRING_ARRAY(
  JSON '{"fruits": ["apples", "oranges", "grapes"]}', '$.fruits'
  ) AS string_array;
```

Combine `JSON_EXTRACT_STRING_ARRAY` with `CAST` and `UNNEST` to extract strings and convert them to a typed SQL array.

```googlesql
SELECT ARRAY(
  SELECT CAST(integer_element AS INT64)
  FROM UNNEST(
    JSON_EXTRACT_STRING_ARRAY('[1, 2, 3]', '$')
  ) AS integer_element
) AS integer_array;
```

The `JSON_QUERY_ARRAY` function extracts a JSON array and converts it to a SQL `ARRAY<JSON>` or `ARRAY<JSON-formatted STRING>` value.

```googlesql
SELECT JSON_QUERY_ARRAY(
  JSON '{"fruits": ["apples", "oranges", "grapes"]}', '$.fruits'
  ) AS json_array;
```

Combine `JSON_QUERY_ARRAY` with `CAST` and `UNNEST` to extract JSON array elements and convert them to a specific SQL type.

```googlesql
SELECT ARRAY(
  SELECT CAST(integer_element AS INT64)
  FROM UNNEST(
    JSON_QUERY_ARRAY('[1, 2, 3]','$')
  ) AS integer_element
) AS integer_array;
```

The `JSON_QUERY_ARRAY` function accepts both dot-notation with quoted keys and bracket-notation to access the same array.

```googlesql
SELECT JSON_QUERY_ARRAY('{"fruits": ["apples", "oranges", "grapes"]}', '$.fruits') AS string_array;

SELECT JSON_QUERY_ARRAY('{"fruits": ["apples", "oranges", "grapes"]}', '$."fruits"') AS string_array;
```

The `JSON_VALUE_ARRAY` function extracts a JSON array of scalar values and returns them as a SQL `ARRAY<STRING>` with quotes removed.

```googlesql
SELECT JSON_VALUE_ARRAY(
  JSON '{"fruits": ["apples", "oranges", "grapes"]}', '$.fruits'
  ) AS string_array;
```

The `LAX_BOOL` function converts JSON numbers to boolean: 0 becomes `FALSE`, and any non-zero value becomes `TRUE`.

```googlesql
SELECT LAX_BOOL(JSON '10') AS result;

SELECT LAX_BOOL(JSON '0') AS result;
```

The `LAX_DOUBLE` function converts JSON numbers, strings representing numbers, and booleans to SQL `DOUBLE` without raising errors on incompatible types.

```googlesql
SELECT LAX_DOUBLE(JSON '9.8') AS result;

SELECT LAX_DOUBLE(JSON '9') AS result;
```

The `LAX_DOUBLE` function parses JSON string values as numbers and converts them to `DOUBLE`, returning `NULL` if parsing fails.

```googlesql
SELECT LAX_DOUBLE(JSON '"10"') AS result;

SELECT LAX_DOUBLE(JSON '"1.1"') AS result;
```

The `LAX_FLOAT` function converts JSON numbers, strings representing numbers, and booleans to SQL `FLOAT` without raising errors on incompatible types.

```googlesql
SELECT LAX_FLOAT(JSON '9.8') AS result;

SELECT LAX_FLOAT(JSON '9') AS result;
```

The `LAX_FLOAT` function parses JSON string values as numbers and converts them to `FLOAT`, returning `NULL` if parsing fails.

```googlesql
SELECT LAX_FLOAT(JSON '"10"') AS result;

SELECT LAX_FLOAT(JSON '"1.1"') AS result;
```

The `LAX_INT32` function converts JSON numbers, strings representing numbers, and booleans to SQL `INT32` without raising errors on out-of-range values.

```googlesql
SELECT LAX_INT32(JSON '10') AS result;

SELECT LAX_INT32(JSON '10.0') AS result;
```

The `LAX_INT32` function parses JSON string values as numbers and converts to `INT32` with rounding, returning `NULL` if parsing fails.

```googlesql
SELECT LAX_INT32(JSON '"10"') AS result;

SELECT LAX_INT32(JSON '"1.1"') AS result;
```

The `LAX_INT32` function converts JSON booleans to `INT32`: `true` becomes 1, `false` becomes 0.

```googlesql
SELECT LAX_INT32(JSON 'true') AS result;

SELECT LAX_INT32(JSON 'false') AS result;
```

The `LAX_INT64` function converts JSON numbers, strings representing numbers, and booleans to SQL `INT64` without raising errors on out-of-range values.

```googlesql
SELECT LAX_INT64(JSON '10') AS result;

SELECT LAX_INT64(JSON '10.0') AS result;
```

The `LAX_INT64` function parses JSON string values as numbers and converts to `INT64` with rounding, returning `NULL` if parsing fails.

```googlesql
SELECT LAX_INT64(JSON '"10"') AS result;

SELECT LAX_INT64(JSON '"1.1"') AS result;
```

The `LAX_STRING` function converts JSON strings, numbers, and booleans to SQL `STRING` without raising errors on incompatible types.

```googlesql
SELECT LAX_STRING(JSON '"purple"') AS result;

SELECT LAX_STRING(JSON '10') AS result;
```

The `LAX_STRING` function converts JSON booleans to the string literals "true" or "false".

```googlesql
SELECT LAX_STRING(JSON 'true') AS result;

SELECT LAX_STRING(JSON 'false') AS result;
```

The `LAX_UINT32` function converts JSON numbers, strings representing numbers, and booleans to SQL `UINT32`, returning `NULL` for negative values or out-of-range numbers.

```googlesql
SELECT LAX_UINT32(JSON '10') AS result;

SELECT LAX_UINT32(JSON '10.0') AS result;
```

The `LAX_UINT32` function parses JSON string values as numbers and converts to `UINT32`, returning `NULL` if parsing fails or the value is negative.

```googlesql
SELECT LAX_UINT32(JSON '"10"') AS result;

SELECT LAX_UINT32(JSON '"1.1"') AS result;
```

The `LAX_UINT64` function converts JSON numbers, strings representing numbers, and booleans to SQL `UINT64`, returning `NULL` for negative values or out-of-range numbers.

```googlesql
SELECT LAX_UINT64(JSON '10') AS result;

SELECT LAX_UINT64(JSON '10.0') AS result;
```

The `LAX_UINT64` function parses JSON string values as numbers and converts to `UINT64`, returning `NULL` if parsing fails or the value is negative.

```googlesql
SELECT LAX_UINT64(JSON '"10"') AS result;

SELECT LAX_UINT64(JSON '"1.1"') AS result;
```

The NEW operator with map constructor syntax creates a protocol buffer by specifying field names and their values, supporting nested structures and arrays.

```googlesql
NEW Universe {
  name: "Sol"
  closest_planets: ["Mercury", "Venus", "Earth" ]
  star {
    radius_miles: 432,690
    age: 4,603,000,000
  }
  constellations: [{
    name: "Libra"
    index: 0
  }, {
    name: "Scorpio"
    index: 1
  }]
  all_planets: (SELECT planets FROM SolTable)
}
```

Use `SET` with multiple variables and a `SELECT AS STRUCT` query. The `STRUCT` fields are unpacked by position into the corresponding variables.

```googlesql
DECLARE target_word STRING DEFAULT 'methinks';
DECLARE corpus_count, word_count INT64;

SET (corpus_count, word_count) = (
  SELECT AS STRUCT COUNT(DISTINCT corpus), SUM(word_count)
  FROM shakespeare
  WHERE LOWER(word) = target_word
);

SELECT
  FORMAT('Found %d occurrences of "%s" across %d Shakespeare works',
         word_count, target_word, corpus_count) AS result;
```

Use `EXECUTE IMMEDIATE` with `?` placeholders and a `USING` clause to pass values by position. The values bind to placeholders in left-to-right order.

```googlesql
DECLARE y INT64;
-- y = 1 * (3 + 2) = 5
EXECUTE IMMEDIATE "SELECT ? * (? + 2)" INTO y USING 1, 3;
```

Use `EXECUTE IMMEDIATE` with `@identifier` placeholders and a `USING` clause with `AS` aliases to pass values by name. Named parameters are matched by identifier.

```googlesql
DECLARE y INT64;
-- y = 1 * (3 + 2) = 5
EXECUTE IMMEDIATE "SELECT @a * (@b + 2)" INTO y USING 1 as a, 3 as b;
```

Use `BEGIN...END` to define a block where variables declared inside the block are only visible within that block. Variables declared in an outer scope can be referenced inside, but inner variables are not accessible after `END`.

```googlesql
DECLARE x INT64 DEFAULT 10;
BEGIN
  DECLARE y INT64;
  SET y = x;
  SELECT y;
END;
SELECT x;
```

Use `BEGIN...EXCEPTION WHEN ERROR THEN` to define error handling. If any statement in the `BEGIN` section encounters an error, execution skips remaining statements in that section and runs the statements in the `EXCEPTION` clause instead.

```googlesql
CREATE OR REPLACE PROCEDURE schema1.proc1() BEGIN
  SELECT 1/0;
END;

CREATE OR REPLACE PROCEDURE schema1.proc2() BEGIN
  CALL schema1.proc1();
END;

BEGIN
  CALL schema1.proc2();
EXCEPTION WHEN ERROR THEN
  SELECT "An error occurred when calling schema1.proc2";
END;
```

Use `CASE` with `WHEN` conditions to test each condition in order and execute the first `THEN` block where the condition is true. Each condition is evaluated independently.

```googlesql
DECLARE target_product_id INT64 DEFAULT 103;
CASE
  WHEN
    EXISTS(SELECT 1 FROM schema.products_a WHERE product_id = target_product_id)
    THEN SELECT 'found product in products_a table';
  WHEN
    EXISTS(SELECT 1 FROM schema.products_b WHERE product_id = target_product_id)
    THEN SELECT 'found product in products_b table';
  ELSE
    SELECT 'did not find product';
END CASE;
```

Use `CASE` with a search expression to evaluate the expression once, then test it for equality against each `WHEN` value until a match is found. The first matching branch executes.

```googlesql
DECLARE product_id INT64 DEFAULT 1;
CASE product_id
  WHEN 1 THEN
    SELECT CONCAT('Product one');
  WHEN 2 THEN
    SELECT CONCAT('Product two');
  ELSE
    SELECT CONCAT('Invalid product');
END CASE;
```

Use `IF` to test a condition, `ELSEIF` for additional conditions, and `ELSE` for the default case. The first condition that is true executes its statement list.

```googlesql
DECLARE target_product_id INT64 DEFAULT 103;
IF EXISTS(SELECT 1 FROM schema.products
           WHERE product_id = target_product_id) THEN
  SELECT CONCAT('found product ', CAST(target_product_id AS STRING));
  ELSEIF EXISTS(SELECT 1 FROM schema.more_products
           WHERE product_id = target_product_id) THEN
  SELECT CONCAT('found product from more_products table',
  CAST(target_product_id AS STRING));
ELSE
  SELECT CONCAT('did not find product ', CAST(target_product_id AS STRING));
END IF;
```

Add a label before `BEGIN` and use `BREAK label_name` to exit the block immediately. This is useful for early termination from nested structures.

```googlesql
label_1: BEGIN
  SELECT 1;
  BREAK label_1;
  SELECT 2; -- Unreached
END;
```

Labels can be reused in non-overlapping sections of code. Each labeled block or loop can have the same label name as long as they do not nest.

```googlesql
label_1: BEGIN
  BREAK label_1;
END;

label_2: BEGIN
  BREAK label_2;
END;

label_1: BEGIN
  BREAK label_1;
END;
```

A label and a variable can share the same name in the same scope without conflict. The context (usage as a label vs. a variable) determines which one is being referenced.

```googlesql
label_1: BEGIN
   DECLARE label_1 INT64;
   BREAK label_1;
END;
```

When closing a labeled block with `END`, you can optionally repeat the label name after `END` to clarify which block is being closed.

```googlesql
label_1: BEGIN
  BREAK label_1;
END label_1;
```

The label name after `END` is optional. You can close a labeled block with `END` alone, and the scope still ends correctly.

```googlesql
label_1: BEGIN
  BREAK label_1;
END;
```

You can use `BREAK label_name` inside the `EXCEPTION` clause of a labeled `BEGIN...EXCEPTION` block to exit that block when an error occurs.

```googlesql
label_1: BEGIN
  SELECT 1;
  EXCEPTION WHEN ERROR THEN
    BREAK label_1;
    SELECT 2; -- Unreached
END;
```

Use `LOOP` to create an indefinite loop. The loop body executes repeatedly until you explicitly issue a `BREAK` or `LEAVE` statement.

```googlesql
DECLARE x INT64 DEFAULT 0;
LOOP
  SET x = x + 1;
  IF x >= 10 THEN
    LEAVE;
  END IF;
END LOOP;
SELECT x;
```

Use `REPEAT` to execute a block of statements, then test a condition at the end. The loop continues executing until the condition is true.

```googlesql
DECLARE x INT64 DEFAULT 0;

REPEAT
  SET x = x + 1;
  SELECT x;
  UNTIL x >= 3
END REPEAT;
```

Use `BREAK` (or its synonym `LEAVE`) inside the loop to exit immediately. This stops execution of the loop body and jumps to the statement after the loop.

```googlesql
DECLARE heads BOOL;
DECLARE heads_count INT64 DEFAULT 0;
LOOP
  SET heads = RAND() < 0.5;
  IF heads THEN
    SELECT 'Heads!';
    SET heads_count = heads_count + 1;
  ELSE
    SELECT 'Tails!';
    BREAK;
  END IF;
END LOOP;
SELECT CONCAT(CAST(heads_count AS STRING), ' heads in a row');
```

Use `CONTINUE` (or its synonym `ITERATE`) to skip remaining statements in the current iteration and jump back to the start of the loop.

```googlesql
DECLARE heads BOOL;
DECLARE heads_count INT64 DEFAULT 0;
LOOP
  SET heads = RAND() < 0.5;
  IF heads THEN
    SELECT 'Heads!';
    SET heads_count = heads_count + 1;
    CONTINUE;
  END IF;
  SELECT 'Tails!';
  BREAK;
END LOOP;
SELECT CONCAT(CAST(heads_count AS STRING), ' heads in a row');
```

Use `BEGIN TRANSACTION` to start a transaction, execute your statements, and issue `COMMIT TRANSACTION` to apply all changes atomically. If any statement fails or you issue `ROLLBACK TRANSACTION`, all changes are undone.

```googlesql
BEGIN TRANSACTION;

-- Create a temporary table of new arrivals from warehouse #1
CREATE TEMP TABLE tmp AS
SELECT * FROM myschema.NewArrivals WHERE warehouse = 'warehouse #1';

-- Delete the matching records from the original table.
DELETE myschema.NewArrivals WHERE warehouse = 'warehouse #1';

-- Merge the matching records into the Inventory table.
MERGE myschema.Inventory AS I
USING tmp AS T
ON I.product = T.product
WHEN NOT MATCHED THEN
 INSERT(product, quantity, supply_constrained)
 VALUES(product, quantity, false)
WHEN MATCHED THEN
 UPDATE SET quantity = I.quantity + T.quantity;

DROP TABLE tmp;

COMMIT TRANSACTION;
```

Use `COMMIT TRANSACTION` (or `COMMIT` alone) to apply all changes made within the open transaction permanently to the database.

```googlesql
BEGIN TRANSACTION;

-- SQL statements for the transaction go here.

COMMIT TRANSACTION;
```

Use `ROLLBACK TRANSACTION` inside an exception handler to undo all changes made within the transaction if an error is caught. This restores the database to its state before the transaction began.

```googlesql
BEGIN

  BEGIN TRANSACTION;
  INSERT INTO myschema.NewArrivals
    VALUES ('top load washer', 100, 'warehouse #1');
  -- Trigger an error.
  SELECT 1/0;
  COMMIT TRANSACTION;

EXCEPTION WHEN ERROR THEN
  -- Roll back the transaction inside the exception handler.
  SELECT @@error.message;
  ROLLBACK TRANSACTION;
END;
```

Use `CALL` with the procedure name and arguments. For output parameters, declare a variable and pass it as an argument; the procedure populates the variable, which you can then select.

```googlesql
DECLARE retCode INT64;
-- Procedure signature: (IN account_id STRING, OUT retCode INT64)
CALL mySchema.UpdateSomeTables('someAccountId', retCode);
SELECT retCode;
```

This query demonstrates the ANY TYPE templated parameter, which allows a function to accept arguments of any data type at call time. The function body is validated only when the function is invoked, so the same function can work with integers, floats, or other compatible types.

```googlesql
CREATE TEMP FUNCTION AddFourAndDivideAny(x ANY TYPE, y ANY TYPE)
AS (
  (x + 4) / y
);

SELECT
  AddFourAndDivideAny(3, 4) AS integer_input,
  AddFourAndDivideAny(1.59, 3.14) AS floating_point_input;
```

This query creates a JavaScript UDF that applies a regex pattern to find all lowercase letters in the input string. The function body requires a raw string literal to preserve the regex syntax without escaping.

```googlesql
CREATE TEMP FUNCTION ExtractLetters(x STRING)
RETURNS STRING
LANGUAGE js
AS r'''
var re = /[a-z]/g;
return x.match(re);
''';

SELECT val, ExtractLetters(val) AS result
FROM UNNEST(['ab-c', 'd_e', '!']) AS val;
```

This query defines a JavaScript UDF with conditional logic that checks the current hour and returns a different message accordingly. Multi-statement JavaScript function bodies require a raw string literal to properly handle the code formatting.

```googlesql
CREATE TEMP FUNCTION CustomGreeting(a STRING)
RETURNS STRING
LANGUAGE js
AS r'''
  var d = new Date();
  if (d.getHours() < 12) {
    return 'Good Morning, ' + a + '!';
  } else {
    return 'Good Evening, ' + a + '!';
  }
''';

SELECT CustomGreeting(names) as everyone
FROM UNNEST(["Hannah", "Max", "Jakob"]) AS names;
```

This query creates a JavaScript UDF where the second and third parameters have default values that are used when arguments are not provided at call time. Default values simplify function calls by allowing you to omit trailing arguments.

```googlesql
CREATE TEMP FUNCTION AddValues(x INT64, y INT64 DEFAULT 50, z INT64 DEFAULT 100)
RETURNS INT64
LANGUAGE js
AS r'''
  return x*y*z;
''';

SELECT AddValues(1, 2) AS result;
```

This query creates a JavaScript UDF with a recursive helper function that traverses nested objects to find and sum all values associated with the key "foo". The main function parses a JSON string and passes it to the recursive summing logic, demonstrating how JavaScript UDFs can implement complex custom logic.

```googlesql
CREATE TEMP FUNCTION SumFieldsNamedFoo(json_row STRING)
RETURNS FLOAT64
LANGUAGE js
AS r'''
function SumFoo(obj) {
  var sum = 0;
  for (var field in obj) {
    if (obj.hasOwnProperty(field) && obj[field] != null) {
      if (typeof obj[field] == "object") {
        sum += SumFoo(obj[field]);
      } else if (field == "foo") {
        sum += obj[field];
      }
    }
  }
  return sum;
}
var row = JSON.parse(json_row);
return SumFoo(row);
''';

WITH
  Input AS (
    SELECT
      STRUCT(1 AS foo, 2 AS bar, STRUCT('foo' AS x, 3.14 AS foo) AS baz) AS s,
      10 AS foo
    UNION ALL
    SELECT NULL, 4 AS foo
    UNION ALL
    SELECT
      STRUCT(NULL, 2 AS bar, STRUCT('fizz' AS x, 1.59 AS foo) AS baz) AS s,
      NULL AS foo
  )
SELECT
  TO_JSON_STRING(t) AS json_row,
  SumFieldsNamedFoo(TO_JSON_STRING(t)) AS foo_sum
FROM Input AS t;
```

This query creates a temporary Lua UDF that returns a string containing escape sequences for newlines. Since the function body contains escape sequences, a raw string literal is required to prevent the escape sequences from being interpreted by GoogleSQL.

```googlesql
CREATE TEMP FUNCTION Alphabet()
RETURNS STRING
LANGUAGE lua
AS r'''
  return 'A\nB\nC';
''';

SELECT Alphabet() AS characters;
```

This query creates a Lua UDF where the second and third parameters have default values that are used when arguments are omitted. Default values allow you to call the function with fewer arguments than the full parameter list.

```googlesql
CREATE TEMP FUNCTION AddValues(x INT64, y INT64 DEFAULT 50, z INT64 DEFAULT 100)
RETURNS INT64
LANGUAGE lua
AS r'''
  return x*y*z;
''';

SELECT AddValues(1, 2) AS result;
```

Runtime variables must be declared with DECLARE statements before use in a script. This example declares one string variable with a default value and two integer variables without defaults, showing both single-declaration and multi-declaration syntax.

```googlesql
DECLARE target_word STRING DEFAULT 'methinks';
DECLARE corpus_count, word_count INT64;
```
